-- Rodobens, Tam, Vale, Arauco, Penoles, BMV: Latin America Equity Preview
-- B y   N a t h a n   G i l l
-- 2010-09-22T07:16:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-22/rodobens-vale-arauco-penoles-latin-america-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Latin American trading. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous
close.  The  MSCI Latin America Index  fell 1.1 percent to 4,186.64.
In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-traded class of
stock.  Brazil  Rodobens Negocios Imobiliarios SA  (RDNI3 BZ): The real-
estate company approved the sale of 70 million reais of
promissory notes maturing in 90 days. The shares were unchanged
at 16.8 reais.  Tam SA  (TAMM4 BZ): South America’s biggest carrier by
passengers said it will boost its presence in Asia through a
cooperation agreement with Japan’s  All Nippon Airways Co.  to
connect flights between Tokyo and Sao Paulo, according to a
company statement. Tam’s shares were unchanged at 38.5 reais.  Vale SA  (VALE3 BZ): The world’s largest iron-ore producer
said it’s concluding the commissioning of its Nova Caledonia and
Onca Puma mining projects, and Onca Puma should be commercially
operable by January, according to a company statement. The
company said in a separate statement it bought 51 percent of
Sociedade de Desenvolvimento do Corredor do Norte SA, a
logistics company owned by Insitec SGPS SA to support its
operations in Africa. The shares rose 0.3 percent to 48.25 reais.  Chile  Banco Santander Chile  (BSAN CC): Standard & Poor’s assigned
an A+ rating to Santander’s $200 million floating-rate senior
unsecured notes due in 2011 and affirmed Chile’s largest
lender’s “stable” credit rating outlook, according to a
statement on S&P’s newswire. The shares fell 2.8 percent to
45.69 pesos.  Parque Arauco SA  (PARAUCO CC): The shopping center
developer and operator agreed to pay $2 million for a 67 percent
stake in Peruvian real-estate company Altek Trading SAC,
according to a company statement posted on the website of
Chile’s securities regulator. The shares climbed 1.1 percent to
929.99 pesos.  Mexico  Bolsa Mexicana de Valores SAB  (BOLSAA MM): The operator of
the nation’s securities exchange will pay a dividend of 96
centavos per outstanding share on Sept. 30, the company said in
a statement. The shares declined 1.1 percent to 21.66 pesos.  Industrias Penoles SAB  (PE&OLES* MM): Mexico’s largest
silver producer said it prepaid the dollar and peso balance on a
syndicated bank loan expiring June 2011, according to a company
statement. The shares rose 1.3 percent to 303.68 pesos.  To contact the reporters on this story:
